<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-11T14:29:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-11T14:29:00-05:00" n="574" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d574">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1268</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Francis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Vologda</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-11T22:00:00+02:31"><hi rend="italic">March 11,
                                            1918, 10 p.m.</hi></date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 12, 11.37
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>5. <persName corresp="#p_MLHS1">Martin</persName><note n="1" xml:id="d574fn1"><persName corresp="#p_MLHS1">Lieut, (later
                                        Capt.) Hugh S. Martin</persName>, assistant military
                                    attaché.</note> wires several hundred marines landed at Murman,
                                more troops expected and that he participated by invitation in
                                meeting with Russian, British, French officers who are organizing to
                                defend Murman Railway from threatened or probable attack by Germans.
                                He says that he saw a telegram from <persName corresp="#p_TLDB1">Trotsky</persName> approving of concerted action, and all
                                regretted that no American officers on the ground to
                                participate.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_FDR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>